Phase 1: The FinOps Network Foundation

Before we deploy any servers, we need a Virtual Private Cloud (VPC). A poorly designed network is where many hidden AWS costs originate (especially data transfer and NAT Gateway fees).

Here is the exact networking design we need to build in our primary region (e.g., us-east-1):

1. The VPC and Subnets
We need high availability across two Availability Zones (AZs) for the Load Balancer, but we want to tightly control where resources live.

Step 1:  Navigate to the VPC dashboard 

1.Log into your AWS Management Console.
2.Ensure you are in your preferred region (e.g., N. Virginia - us-east-1) using the dropdown in the top right corner.
3.In the search bar at the top, type VPC and click on the VPC service.
4.In the VPC dashboard, click the orange Create VPC button.

Step 2: Configure the "VPC and more" Wizard

AWS gives you two options here. We want to use the visual wizard because it automatically handles the complex route tables for us.

1.Under Resources to create, select VPC and more.
2.Under Name tag auto-generation, leave the checkbox checked and type finops-project in the text box. (AWS will use this prefix to neatly name all your subnets and route tables).
3.Under IPv4 CIDR block, leave it as the default 10.0.0.0/16.
4.Keep IPv6 CIDR block set to No IPv6 CIDR block.
5.Keep Tenancy set to Default.


Step 3: Configuration of Availability Zones and subnets

Here we set up our multi-Az architecuture
1.Under Number of Availability Zones (AZs), select 2. (It will likely select us-east-1a and us-east-1b automatically).
2.Under Number of public subnets, select 2.
3.Under Number of private subnets, select 4.

      Note: The wizard only lets us choose "Private". Later, we will use two of these for our EC2 instances (App layer) and two strictly for our RDS database (Data layer).

4.You can leave the "Customize subnets CIDR blocks" section as the default values AWS provides.

Step 4: Apply the FinOps Settings (Crucial Step)

This is where we implement our cost saving measures:

1.NAT gateways ($): Select In 1 AZ.

Why: Selecting "1 per AZ" doubles your baseline NAT Gateway costs. Selecting "In 1 AZ" gives our private subnets internet access through a single gateway.

2.VPC endpoints: Select S3 Gateway.

Why: This is our "secret weapon." It creates a free, private tunnel directly to S3. Without this, your EC2 instances would route S3 traffic through the NAT Gateway, and AWS would charge you data processing fees for your own images.

3.Leave DNS options checked (both "Enable DNS resolution" and "Enable DNS hostnames" should be checked).

Step 5: Review and Create 

1.Look at the Preview panel on the right side of the screen. You should see a diagram showing your VPC, your subnets, 1 Internet Gateway, 1 NAT Gateway, and 1 S3 Endpoint.

2.Click the orange Create VPC button at the bottom.

3.Wait a few moments. AWS will run through a checklist, provisioning all the route tables and attaching the gateways automatically. Once it says "Success", click View VPC.

Step 6: Rename the Database Subnets

To make things easier for ourselves when we build the database, let's clearly label our subnets.

1.On the left-hand menu, click on Subnets.
2.In the search bar, type finops-project-private. You will see four subnets.3.We need to reserve two of these for the database. Look at the AZ column to find one in us-east-1a and one in us-east-1b.
4.Hover over the name of one of them, click the small pencil icon to edit the name, and change it from finops-project-private... to finops-project-isolated-db-1a. Click Sa
5.Do the same for a subnet in the other AZ, naming it finops-project-isolated-db-1b.
6.(Optional) You can edit the Route Tables for these two "isolated" subnets and remove the route that points to the NAT Gateway ( 0.0.0.0/0 -> nat-... ) to ensure the database has zero outbound internet access for maximum security.


